Maren Morris was nominated for 2019 Grammy Awards for Record Of The Year ('The Middle'), Best Pop Duo/Group Performance ('The Middle'), Best Country Solo Performance ('Mona Lisas And Mad Hatters'), Best Country Duo/Group Performance ('Dear Hate') and Best Country Song ('Dear Hate').

Brandi Carlile received several nominations in the 2019 Grammy Awards related to her album 'By The Way, I Forgive You': Record Of The Year ('The Joke'), Album Of The Year (By The Way, I Forgive You), Song Of The Year ('The Joke'), Best American Roots Performance ('The Joke'), Best American Roots Song ('The Joke'), Best Americana Album (By The Way, I Forgive You).

Super-producer Dave Cobb was all over the 2019 Grammy Award nominations, with Record Of The Year ('The Joke' - Brandi Carlile), Album Of The Year ('By The Way, I Forgive You' - Brandi Carlile), Song Of The Year ('The Joke' - Brandi Carlile) Best American Roots Song ('The Joke' - Brandi Carlile).

Kacey Musgraves' Golden Hour received an Album Of The Year nomination in the 2019 Grammy Awards and Golden Hour was also nominated for Best Country Album. Musgraves was also nominated for Best Country Solo Performance ('Butterflies')  and Best Country Song ('Space Cowboy' written with Luke Laird and Shane McAnally)
Lauren Daigle was nominated for two 2019 Grammy Awards: Best Contemporary Christian Music Performance/Song ('You Say') and Best Contemporary Christian Music Album (Look Up Child).
John Prine was nominated for three separate 2019 Grammy Awards: Best Americana Album (Tree Of Forgiveness) and twice in Best American Roots Song ('Knockin' On Your Screen Door' and 'Summer's End').

Super-producer Dave Cobb was all over the 2019 Grammy Award nominations, with Record Of The Year ('The Joke' - Brandi Carlile), Album Of The Year ('By The Way, I Forgive You' - Brandi Carlile), Song Of The Year ('The Joke' - Brandi Carlile) Best American Roots Song ('The Joke' - Brandi Carlile).

Lauren Daigle was nominated for two 2019 Grammy Awards: Best Contemporary Christian Music Performance/Song ('You Say') and Best Contemporary Christian Music Album (Look Up Child).
John Prine was nominated for three separate 2019 Grammy Awards: Best Americana Album (Tree Of Forgiveness) and twice in Best American Roots Song ('Knockin' On Your Screen Door' and 'Summer's End').

Chris Stapleton's 2019 Grammy Award nominations included Best Country Album (From A Room: Volume 2), Best Pop Duo/Group Performance ('Say Something,' with Justin Timberlake), and Best Country Solo Performance ('Millionaire').

Julie Cunningham is one of Ted Bundy's three Colorado victims. She disappeared on March 15, 1975 from Vail. In his 11th-hour confessions from death row 14 years later, Bundy confessed to luring Cunningham to his car, incapacitating, abducting, raping and killing her.(Photo: File photo)

Carol DaRonch testifies at a pre-sentencing hearing for convicted murder Ted Bundy as Judge Edward Cowart listens, July 28, 1979, in Miami.  Bundy was convicted of kidnapping DaRonch from a Salt Lake City suburb in 1974.(Photo: AP)
On December 30, 1977, Bundy escapes the Garfield County Jail and vanishes. This photo shows a supposed footprint left by Bundy during the escape.(Photo: Colorado's 9th Judicial District)

Judge Edward Cowart reads the sentence to Theodore Bundy and his defense attorney Margaret Good, backs to camera, July 31, 1979, in Miami.  Bundy was sentenced to death in the electric chair for the murders of two Chi Omega sorority sisters in 1978.(Photo: AP)

Theodore Bundy smiles when asked by reporters if he had anything to say to Seattle, Oct. 3, 1978. Bundy replied "Yeah, I wish were there, me and King Tut."  Bundy won a two-month delay in Tallahassee in his trial on brutally slaying two Florida State University coeds. Bundy, 31, represented self after four courts denied him the attorney of his choice, Millard Farmer.  (AP Photo)(Photo: DJ, ASSOCIATED PRESS)

On June 7, 1977, suspected killer Ted Bundy leaped from a second-story courthouse window while awaiting trial for the murder of Caryn Campbell. Aspen authorities and residents took up the search for him immediately. Some were described as "somewhat miffed" at the escape and resulting search, having described the lax security around Bundy as "patently naive, and bordering on criminally stupid." Bundy would remain at large for a week.

Convicted kidnapper and accused killer Ted Bundy is led into the Pitkin County courthouse by Deputy Peter Murphy, left, and Rick Kralicek for a hearing in Aspen, Colo. Bundy, who was being charged for murder, jumped out of a second-story window during a court recess on June 7, 1977. He was recaptured while trying to flee town on June 13, 1977.

1997: Kenny Holmes (No. 18 overall) Defensive End, Miami (Fla.) Holmes was selected to the Tennessee Oilers in the first season of transition from Houston to Nashville and made an immediate impact with seven sacks in his rookie as a rotational lineman. Holmes played four solid seasons in Tennessee before moving on to the New York Giants.

1998: Kevin Dyson (No. 16 overall) Wide Receiver, Utah Forever the final, and most important, piece of the Music City Miracle, Dyson had an otherwise up and down career. Dyson had an 825-yard season in 2001, his best as a Titan.

1999: Jevon Kearse (No. 16 overall) Defensive End, Florida The Freak. Kearse had his 14.5-sack season in 1999, one of the best rookie efforts in NFL history. After two more double-digit seasons, Kearse finished out his first stint with the Titans and signed with Philly. And don't forget that The Freak returned in 2008.

2000: Keith Bulluck (No. 16 overall) Linebacker, Syracuse Bulluck is one of the best first-round selections in Titans and Oilers history. Three-time All-Pro, five straight seasons of at least 125 total tackles and excellent leadership are only some of the things Bulluck brought to the franchise in his 10 seasons.

2002 Albert Haynesworth (No. 15 overall) Defensive Tackle, Tennessee Haynesworth is remembered for a couple of irksome reasons. First, his stomping of Dallas center Andre Gurode earned Haynesowrth a five-game suspension. It was the second multi-game suspension an on-field incident for only the second time in NFL history. Also, he earned a seven-year, $100 million deal from Washington, a contract that looks bloated even now.

2003: Andre Woolfolk (No. 28 overall) Defensive Back, Oklahoma

Woolfolk was a major disappointment and the worst of the bunch. He started 12 games in four seasons, caught three interceptions (all from David Carr) and was out of the league after 2006.

2005: Adam Jones (No. 6 overall)
Defensive Back, West Virginia

A solid rookie season, a good second season, and a year-long suspension marked the three years of "Pacman" in Nashville. Jones had four punt-return TDs in two seasons and just started to bloom as a corner when he was suspended for the 2007 season. By 2008, he was in Dallas.
2006: Vince Young (No. 3 overall) Quarterback, Texas:
2007: Michael Griffin (No. 19 overall) Defensive Back, Texas

Caption: House Beautiful magazine announced that its second annual Whole Home Concept House will be built in Belle Meade in partnership with Nashville area custom builder Castle Homes. This show house will be devoted to designs and ideas to create a home that promotes wellness and better living. Wellness Within Your Walls, which promotes health and sustainability in home design, will also participate in the project.

The almost 6,000 square foot home, will be in the English Arts and Crafts style and sit on a pretty ¾ acre home site and is being built in the Belle Meade area of Nashville. This will be a design-build project for Castle Homes who collaborated with architect Kevin Coffey, C. Kevin Coffey Dwellings and Design. The team was inspired by early 20th century architect C. F. A. Voysey, who embraced the simplicity of the Arts and Crafts movement.  The home will be open for tour in October and featured in House Beautiful magazine in November.
The House Beautiful Whole Home Concept House will be open to the public from Friday, October 18th, through November 3rd, and proceeds will benefit the Nashville Symphony.
"It is a strong economic indicator and reflection of the Nashville housing market that House Beautiful magazine wants to partner on a home of this caliber," said Alan Looney, president, Castle Homes.
Alan Looney, president of Castle Homes, was joined by the team for House Beautiful at the building site of the fall Whole Home Concept House being built in Nashville.

“In the 2018 Whole Home Concept House, we introduced new design concepts, spaces and products focused on celebrating healthier and happier cooking and living. Every decision in the home, large and small, was made with the goal of wellness of body, mind and family.” said Matthew Quinn of Design Galleria Kitchen and Bath Studio.

"This year, we will work with designers to get their “design prescription” for making homes happier, healthier, and smarter…and as always, beautiful. This house will illustrate these concepts through layout, product, and inspiration, each providing actionable ideas that readers and visitors can implement in their own homes,” said Carisha Swanson, Director, House Beautiful Whole Home Concept House.

“We know that thoughtful decisions about your home can lead to a happier, healthier life. It’s so important for us to tell the story of this incredible project across every platform," said Joanna Saltz, Editorial Director of House Beautiful.

“We are honored to partner with House Beautiful, Castle Homes, and Design Galleria Kitchen and Bath Studio in the design/build of the Whole Home Concept House,” said Jillian Pritchard Cooke, founder of Wellness Within Your Walls.

Ike White coached football, basketball, track, baseball, golf, and wrestling during his 25-year coaching career and served as a member of the TSSAA Board of Control from 2006 until his retirement in 2015.

Jabbo Hessey is a longtime teacher and coach in the Nashville area who served as an official for the TSSAA track and field state championships for 48 years. Hessey served as the Director of the TSSAA State Track Meet for 11 years and retired after the 2016 state track meet.

Jim Barr was an official, coach, and administrator in the Nashville area for 49 years until his retirement in 2010. Barr was named as the TIAAA Athletic Director of the Year and TSSAA Distinguished Service Award winner in 1996.

Mickey Marley received numerous coach of the year honors during his 27-year tenure as head football coach at USJ. Marley was inducted into the Jackson/Madison Co. Sports Hall of Fame, the Franklin High School Sports Hall of Fame, and the Tennessee Football Coaches Association Hall of Fame

Tom Weathers spent 29 years as the head football coach at Red Bank, winning a Class 5A state title in 2000. Weathers received the TSSAA Distinguished Service Award in 1988, and the Red Bank football field is named after him.

Tommy Colvin has been a girls basketball coach for over 40 years in West Tennessee and won state titles in 1979 and 1985 at Humboldt. His teams have made seven appearances in the state tournament, including a runner-up finish in 2004 with Peabody.
Joe George was the head baseball coach at Marshall County for more than 35 years and won 3 TSSAA State Baseball Championships (1983, 1993, 1994).

The recent wave of the Catholic clergy sex abuse crisis was a catalyst for the group's creation, but it is focused on helping all children and holding all entities accountable. (Photo: Calvin Mattheis/News Sentinel)

Amanda Cormier was sexually abused as a teen by former Dr. Larry Nassar.  She testified at his sentencing hearing last year. Now she wants to help change the law in Tennessee. (Photo: Shelley Mays / The Tennessean)

Date: Published 6:00 a.m. CT Feb. 1, 2019 | Updated 11:02 a.m. CT Feb. 1, 2019
Caption: 1997: Kenny Holmes (No. 18 overall) Defensive End, Miami (Fla.) Holmes was selected to the Tennessee Oilers in the first season of transition from Houston to Nashville and made an immediate impact with seven sacks in his rookie as a rotational lineman. Holmes played four solid seasons in Tennessee before moving on to the New York Giants.

1998: Kevin Dyson (No. 16 overall) Wide Receiver, Utah Forever the final, and most important, piece of the Music City Miracle, Dyson had an otherwise up and down career. Dyson had an 825-yard season in 2001, his best as a Titan.

1999: Jevon Kearse (No. 16 overall) Defensive End, Florida The Freak. Kearse had his 14.5-sack season in 1999, one of the best rookie efforts in NFL history. After two more double-digit seasons, Kearse finished out his first stint with the Titans and signed with Philly. And don't forget that The Freak returned in 2008.

2000: Keith Bulluck (No. 16 overall) Linebacker, Syracuse Bulluck is one of the best first-round selections in Titans and Oilers history. Three-time All-Pro, five straight seasons of at least 125 total tackles and excellent leadership are only some of the things Bulluck brought to the franchise in his 10 seasons.

2002 Albert Haynesworth (No. 15 overall) Defensive Tackle, Tennessee Haynesworth is remembered for a couple of irksome reasons. First, his stomping of Dallas center Andre Gurode earned Haynesowrth a five-game suspension. It was the second multi-game suspension an on-field incident for only the second time in NFL history. Also, he earned a seven-year, $100 million deal from Washington, a contract that looks bloated even now.

2003: Andre Woolfolk (No. 28 overall) Defensive Back, Oklahoma

Woolfolk was a major disappointment and the worst of the bunch. He started 12 games in four seasons, caught three interceptions (all from David Carr) and was out of the league after 2006.

2005: Adam Jones (No. 6 overall)
Defensive Back, West Virginia

A solid rookie season, a good second season, and a year-long suspension marked the three years of "Pacman" in Nashville. Jones had four punt-return TDs in two seasons and just started to bloom as a corner when he was suspended for the 2007 season. By 2008, he was in Dallas.
2006: Vince Young (No. 3 overall) Quarterback, Texas:
2007: Michael Griffin (No. 19 overall) Defensive Back, Texas

2008: Chris Johnson (No. 24 overall)
Running Back, East Carolina

In six seasons with the Titans, Johnson ran for more than 1,000 yards in each.  Johnson has four 10+ TD seasons, a 2,000-yard season and a heavy workload. Is he the best Titans RB ever?

Caption: The combination of a snowy slope and no school Dec. 11, 1962, adds up to an irresistible temptation for these frolicsome children. Not even freezing temperatures can spoil their fun as they speed along on a "sled train" in the front yard of C.W. Butler of Overton Lea Road.

Two young Nashville ladies seem to be having trouble teaching young Bob Johnson, 11, of Fairmont Drive, how to skate on the ice which covers the lake in Centennial Park Dec. 12, 1962. Ellen Johnson, left, 17, the sister of the boy, and Pat Lyne, 16, of Pinehurst Drive, the cousin of the two, are doing their best. The piercing cold of sub-zero temperatures caused fires, electrical failures and death by freezing in Nashville.

Ice skating, which came to Nashville with the Dixie Flyers earlier this year, seems to be gaining popularity here. Charles Tallent of Rockdale Ave., drinks coffee as he cut the ice on the lake in Centennial Park Dec. 13, 1962. The city is slowly escaping from the super cold weather by climbing to a high of 26 degrees above 0.

Miss Jacksonville, Fla., Leslie Ann Hill, 17, builds a snowman to decorate the lawn of her relatives' home in Hendersonville Dec. 25, 1962. Nashville's white Christmas of 5 inches was the first snow this former Nashvillian had seen in seven years. This also was her first white Christmas, as it was for all Nashvillians born since 1935.

Snow-covered automobiles, some stalled and some beginning to stall, try to gain traction on the streets of downtown Nashville Jan. 23, 1963. Four-inch snowfall and high temperatures between zero and eight degrees hit Nashville.

How to spend a cold winter night, and still enjoy the thrill of skates on ice? Easy, just slip on down to Municipal Auditorium as some 150 people of all ages did here Jan. 23, 1963. It's warmer, 65 degrees, instead of below zero like outside.

Automobiles creep cautiously through Broadway as a lone pedestrian braves the elements, umbrella raised against a steady snowfall that blanketed the city with an inch an hour early in the evening Dec. 22, 1963. More than six inches of snow piled up in about six hours in Nashville.

Snow falling in Centennial Park Dec. 22, 1963 makes a cheerful winter atmosphere for Jean Thomson, 17, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. J.A. Thomson of Stinson Road and Gary Smith, 18, of Rosebank Ave., a Vanderbilt University student. All of Tennessee was blanketed white and Memphis got its biggest snowfall of this century with 15 inches, most since March of 1892.

Snow always has its happy side, as the excited expression of Tommy Phillips, 2, proves Dec. 23, 1963. His mother, Mrs. Dudley Phillips of Charlotte Ave., had to take Tommy sledding even before the snow stopped falling.

Suppose a photographer came up to you and asked you to throw a snowball over his head so he could take a "dramatic" photo and impress the boss. Four-year-old Billy Cason of Delaware Ave. obliged Dec. 24, 1963, but his aim was a trifle low, hitting the photographer squarely between the eyes.

Caption: Fox aired its production of "Rent" on Jan. 27, the latest in a recent batch of live musical events on network television. But a broken foot meant most of the show did not air live.
Vanessa Hudgens starred as Maureen in Fox's "Rent."
Singer Tinashe portrayed Mimi in Fox's version of "Rent."

Jordan Fisher and Brennin Hunt starred in the production playing friends Mark and Roger. Hunt broke his foot during the final rehearsal of the show, causing Fox to air the taped rehearsal instead of running the show live on air.

"The Sound of Music Live" (NBC, Dec. 5, 2013): The TV musical trend started with NBC's production of "The Sound of Music," starring country music singer Carrie Underwood as Maria, a governess who tries to help the von Trapp family escape the Nazis.

"Peter Pan Live!" (NBC Dec. 4, 2014): NBC followed that up a year later with "Peter Pan." The musical starred "Get Out" star Allison Williams as the boy who wouldn't grow up with Christopher Walken as his nemesis, Captain Hook.

"The Wiz Live!" (NBC, Dec. 5, 2015): NBC's production, based on a 1975 Broadway musical adaptation of L. Frank Baum's "The Wonderful Wizard of Oz," included Common, Uzo Aduba, David Alan Grier, Mary J. Blige as the Wicked Witch of the West and Shanice Williams as Dorothy.

"Grease Live" ( Fox, Jan. 31, 2016): Fox's first foray into the live musical, starring Vanessa Hudgens,
Juliane Hough and Aaron Tveit. It was based on the 1978 movie starring Olivia Newton John and John Travolta.

1997: Kenny Holmes (No. 18 overall) Defensive End, Miami (Fla.) Holmes was selected to the Tennessee Oilers in the first season of transition from Houston to Nashville and made an immediate impact with seven sacks in his rookie as a rotational lineman. Holmes played four solid seasons in Tennessee before moving on to the New York Giants.

1998: Kevin Dyson (No. 16 overall) Wide Receiver, Utah Forever the final, and most important, piece of the Music City Miracle, Dyson had an otherwise up and down career. Dyson had an 825-yard season in 2001, his best as a Titan.

1999: Jevon Kearse (No. 16 overall) Defensive End, Florida The Freak. Kearse had his 14.5-sack season in 1999, one of the best rookie efforts in NFL history. After two more double-digit seasons, Kearse finished out his first stint with the Titans and signed with Philly. And don't forget that The Freak returned in 2008.

2000: Keith Bulluck (No. 16 overall) Linebacker, Syracuse Bulluck is one of the best first-round selections in Titans and Oilers history. Three-time All-Pro, five straight seasons of at least 125 total tackles and excellent leadership are only some of the things Bulluck brought to the franchise in his 10 seasons.

2002 Albert Haynesworth (No. 15 overall) Defensive Tackle, Tennessee Haynesworth is remembered for a couple of irksome reasons. First, his stomping of Dallas center Andre Gurode earned Haynesowrth a five-game suspension. It was the second multi-game suspension an on-field incident for only the second time in NFL history. Also, he earned a seven-year, $100 million deal from Washington, a contract that looks bloated even now.

2003: Andre Woolfolk (No. 28 overall) Defensive Back, Oklahoma

Woolfolk was a major disappointment and the worst of the bunch. He started 12 games in four seasons, caught three interceptions (all from David Carr) and was out of the league after 2006.

2005: Adam Jones (No. 6 overall)
Defensive Back, West Virginia

A solid rookie season, a good second season, and a year-long suspension marked the three years of "Pacman" in Nashville. Jones had four punt-return TDs in two seasons and just started to bloom as a corner when he was suspended for the 2007 season. By 2008, he was in Dallas.
2006: Vince Young (No. 3 overall) Quarterback, Texas:
2007: Michael Griffin (No. 19 overall) Defensive Back, Texas
